Data Cleaning

#remove rows with missing values
data <- na.omit(data) 
str(data)

#fix customer date
data <- data %>%
  mutate(enrollment_date1 = mdy(data$Dt_Customer))
## Warning: 1311 failed to parse.
data %>%
  mutate(enrollment_date = if_else(is.na(enrollment_date1),dmy(data$Dt_Customer),enrollment_date1))
data <- subset(data, select = -c(enrollment_date1))

#standardize "Education" Field
unique(data$Education)
# assume Undergraduate degree: Basic (1)
# assume Graduate degree: Graduation, Master, 2n Cycle (2)
# assume Doctorate degree: PhD (3)
data <- within(data, Education[Education == 'Basic'] <- 1)
data <- within(data, Education[Education == 'Graduation' | Education == 'Master' |
                                 Education == '2n Cycle'] <- 2)
data <- within(data, Education[Education == 'PhD'] <- 3)

#standardize "Marital_Status" Field
unique(data$Marital_Status)
# assume partner: Together, Married
# assume single: Single, Divorced, Widow, Alone, Absurd, YOLO
data$have_partner <- 1
data <- within(data, have_partner[Marital_Status == 'Together' | Marital_Status == 'Married'] <- 1)
data <- within(data, have_partner[Marital_Status == 'Single' | Marital_Status == 'Divorced' |
                                    Marital_Status == 'Widow' | Marital_Status == 'Alone' | 
                                    Marital_Status == 'Absurd' | Marital_Status == 'YOLO'] <- 0)

#children: add Kidhome+TeenHome into one column, add another column to indicate parents or not
data$children <- data$Kidhome+data$Teenhome
data$is_parent <- 1
data <- within(data, is_parent[children == 0] <- 0)
data$household_size <- data$children+data$have_partner+1

#age
data$age <- 2023-data$Year_Birth

#removing outlier
data <- data %>% filter(age< 90)  
data <- data %>% filter(Income< 600000)

#spent total
data$total_spent <- data$MntWines+data$MntFruits+data$MntMeatProducts+data$MntFishProducts+data$MntSweetProducts+data$MntGoldProds

data$perecent_fruits_spent <- (data$MntFruits/data$total_spent)*100
data$perecent_meat_spent <- (data$MntMeatProducts/data$total_spent)*100
data$perecent_fish_spent <- (data$MntFishProducts/data$total_spent)*100
data$perecent_sweets_spent <- (data$MntSweetProducts/data$total_spent)*100
data$perecent_gold_spent <- (data$MntGoldProds/data$total_spent)*100

#Number of purchases made thru 
data$total_place <- data$NumWebPurchases+data$NumCatalogPurchases+data$NumStorePurchases+data$NumWebVisitsMonth

data$perecent_web <- (data$NumWebPurchases/data$total_place)*100
data$perecent_catalog <- (data$NumCatalogPurchases/data$total_place)*100
data$perecent_store <- (data$NumStorePurchases/data$total_place)*100
data$perecent_web_visit <- (data$NumWebVisitsMonth/data$total_place)*100

#dropping columns

From the first plot, the first principal component captures 22.1% of the total variance in the data. It include variables total_spent, Income, Total_place(number of purchases in all places), has children and Percent_web_visit. This suggests that these variables have a strong correlation with each other, and together they contribute significantly to the variability in the data. It indicates in PC1, these are the customers who have high income, make more purchases across different places, spend more money, have children, and prefer to shop by visiting the company’s website frequently.

The second principal component captures 13.3% of the total variance in the data. It include variables Education, Percent_whine_Spent, Percent_fish_Spent,Percent_fruits_Spent and Number of Deal purchased. This suggests that in PC2, these are the customers who are well-educated, spend more on wine, fish, and fruits, and purchase more deals.

The third principal component captures 6.8% of the total variance in the data. The variables are mostly related to how many campaign customers accepted.

In summary, the PCA analysis has identified three principal components that capture different aspects of the customer data. PC1 captures the general spending habits and website usage of customers, PC2 captures the purchasing habits of customers with respect to certain products, and PC3 captures the tendency of customers to accept campaign offers.

library(caret)

library(dplyr)

clusterData <- as.data.frame(subset(PCAdata, select = c(total_spent, Income, total_place, is_parent,  perecent_web_visit)))

index <- createDataPartition(clusterData$Income, p = 0.7, list = FALSE)

trainCl <- clusterData[index,]
testCl <- clusterData[-index,]

train_scaled <- as.data.frame(scale(trainCl))
test_scaled <- as.data.frame(scale(testCl))


library(cluster)

#Calculating wss
calculate_wss <- function(k) {
  kmeans(clusterData, k)$tot.withinss
}

#Calculating VAF
calculate_var_acct <- function(clusterData, k) {
  km_model <- kmeans(clusterData, k)
  tot_ss <- sum(km_model$withinss) + sum(km_model$betweenss)
  var_acct <- 1 - (km_model$tot.withinss / tot_ss)
  return(var_acct)
}

kmeans_results = list()
wss_values = list()
trainVAF_values = list()
testVAF_values = list()

for (i in 1:10){
  kmeans_results[[i]] = kmeans(train_scaled, centers = i, nstart = 50, iter.max = 100)
  wss_values[[i]] = calculate_wss(i)
  trainVAF_values[[i]] = calculate_var_acct(train_scaled, i)
  testVAF_values[[i]] = calculate_var_acct(test_scaled, i)
}

  train_centers <- kmeans_results[[i]]$centers
  train_sizes <- kmeans_results[[i]]$size
  
  test_clusters <- kmeans(test_scaled, centers = train_centers, nstart = 1)
  
  test_centers <- test_clusters$centers
  test_sizes <- test_clusters$size
  
  results[[i]] <- list(train_centers = train_centers, train_sizes = train_sizes,
                                     test_centers = test_centers, test_sizes = test_sizes)
  
    train_sizes_relative <- results[[i]]$train_sizes / sum(results[[i]]$train_sizes)
  test_sizes_relative <- results[[i]]$test_sizes / sum(results[[i]]$test_sizes)
  print(paste0(i, " clusters:"))
  print("Train Set:")
  print(train_sizes_relative)
  print("Test Set:")
  print(test_sizes_relative)
}

As we can see from the results of the Cluster Analysis, our customers can be separated into two groups with the following characteristics:

Cluster 1: Customers with lower income and greater number of children. They spend less in total, make purchases less frequently and mostly make them online.

Cluster 2: Customers with greater income and fewer number of children. They spend more in total and also make purchases frequently but don’t make them online as often.

    AcceptedCmp1 + AcceptedCmp2 + AcceptedCmp3 > 0 ~ 'High',

  ))

data1 <- data %>%
  mutate(Acceptance = if_else(
    AcceptedCmp1 + AcceptedCmp2 + AcceptedCmp3 + AcceptedCmp4 + AcceptedCmp5 + Response == 0, 0, 1
  ))
set.seed(1112)
data_ml2 <- data1[-c(5,6,7,8,9,11)]
sample=sample(c(TRUE, FALSE), nrow(data_ml2), replace=TRUE, prob=c(0.7,0.3))
train<-data_ml2[sample, ]
test<-data_ml2[!sample, ]
lr=(glm(factor(Acceptance)~ ., data = train,family=binomial(link=logit)))
xp=predict(lr, train,type="response")
